# HostingLint - Cursor AI Rules

## Project Overview
HostingLint is an open-source static analysis toolkit for hosting control panel modules.
Built with TypeScript 5, Node.js 20, npm workspaces monorepo.
See CLAUDE.md for full project context.

## Code Style

### TypeScript
- Strict mode enabled — avoid `any`, use proper types
- Use `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions/literals
- Use `.js` extension in relative import paths (Node16 module resolution)
- Export types from dedicated type files
- Prefer `const` over `let`, never use `var`
- All functions should have JSDoc comments

### File Structure
- Analyzers in `packages/core/src/analyzers/{platform}/`
- Rules in `packages/core/src/rules/`
- Types in `packages/core/src/types.ts`
- CLI in `packages/cli/src/cli.ts`
- Tests mirror source structure in `packages/*/tests/`

## Rule Development

### Adding a New Rule
1. Define the rule in `packages/core/src/rules/index.ts`
2. Follow the `Rule` interface from `types.ts`
3. Add to the appropriate platform array (`phpRules`, `perlRules`, `openpanelRules`)
4. Rule ID format: `{platform}-{category}-{name}` (e.g., `whmcs-deprecated`, `perl-security-taint`)
5. Write tests in `packages/core/tests/analyzers/{platform}.test.ts`
6. Test both positive (detection) and negative (no false positive) cases

### Rule Implementation
- Rules are pure functions: `(code: string, filePath: string) => LintResult[]`
- Use regex pattern matching — no runtime execution
- Always provide `line` and `column` numbers
- Include a `fix` suggestion when possible
- Never throw — return empty array if no issues found

## Testing
- Framework: Vitest with globals
- Test files: `packages/*/tests/**/*.test.ts`
- Run: `npm test`
- Use `describe`/`it`/`expect` pattern
- Test examples in `examples/` directory

## Security Rules
- NEVER execute analyzed code
- NEVER require PHP or Perl runtime
- All analysis is string-based (regex matching)
- File system access is read-only

## Do NOT
- Do not add React or any frontend dependencies
- Do not add unnecessary dependencies
- Do not use `console.log` in library code (only in CLI)
- Do not execute or eval user-provided code
- Do not commit .env files or secrets
- Do not skip TypeScript types
